oslo_messaging/_drivers/impl_rabbit.py.message:
Continuing my comment from patchset 11, I see two choices:
1. do not pass 'durable' as a parameter to this method and only check here 'if rabbit_quorum_queue:'. Similar to rabbit_ha_queues not checking the 'durable' value. The reason for this is the belief that the code has been modified (in this PR) so that durable is True when rabbit_quorum_queue is true.

2. change this code to be something like:

if rabbit_quorum_queue:
    if durable:
        args['x-queue-type'] = 'quorum'
    else:
        LOG something. either exception or warning, your choice, to indicate that even though rabbit_quorum_queue was specified, it wasn't done because durable was false. Or to fail/raise exception so that the operator has to take some action.

3. I guess another choice is to do something like:

if rabbit_quorum_queue:
    args['x-queue-type'] = 'quorum'
    if not durable:
        LOG something or raise exception

I don't know enough to know what the better way might be to deal with this inconsistency but I do believe that the minimum is to inform the user. I tend to the raise exception though because operators won't do anything unless they have to, and thinking that they have rabbit_quorum_queue set when it isn't, could be disastrous in the long run...

This would probably make more sense as a property since it's a calculated value

  @property
  def durable(self):
      return self.amqp_durable_queues or self.rabbit_quorum_queue
